I'm much more sure now :) The second sentence in my previous comment was due to MxNet version conflict. Please forget it. However, my first comment seems true but my solution is syntactically incorrect, semantically correct :) The correct solution, to me of course, is as below:

<pre>
        if self.for_training:
            self.grad_arrays = [[exec_.grad_arrays[i] for exec_ in self.execs <b>if exec_.grad_arrays[i].wait_to_read() or True</b>]
                                for i, name in enumerate(self.arg_names)
                                if name in self.param_names]
        else:
            self.grad_arrays = None

        data_names = [x[0] for x in data_shapes]
        if self.inputs_need_grad:
            self.input_grad_arrays = [[exec_.grad_arrays[i] for exec_ in self.execs <b>if exec_.grad_arrays[i].wait_to_read() or True</b>]
                                      for i, name in enumerate(self.arg_names)
                                      if name in data_names]
</pre>

@piiswrong Hi, I tried dmlc/deepmark-mxnet and it turned out that GTX1060 is definitely faster than GTX750Ti.
(vgg/resnet/alexnet:         GTX1060:46/31/12         GTX750Ti:120/75/26)
But in my SSD example it is just like there is a upper limit to my GTX1060(max to about 45 samples/sec), which didn't happen on my GTX750Ti...Could you give me some suggestions?

